<paragraph blockId="8.[136,1452,1454,1768]" pageId="8" pageNumber="161">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[136,366,1454,1480]" pageId="8" pageNumber="161">Species richness:—</emphasis>
<taxonomicName authorityName="Miller" authorityYear="1754" box="[366,458,1455,1481]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Cactaceae" genus="Opuntia" kingdom="Plantae" order="Caryophyllales" pageId="8" pageNumber="161" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[366,458,1455,1481]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="161">Opuntia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is a genus with wide geographic distribution and comprises approximately 200 species. In 
<collectingCountry box="[166,237,1490,1516]" name="Brazil" pageId="8" pageNumber="161">Brazil</collectingCountry>
, there are 5 species of which ocurr in 
<collectingRegion box="[662,871,1490,1516]" country="Brazil" name="Rio Grande do Sul" pageId="8" pageNumber="161">Rio Grande do Sul</collectingRegion>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Carneiro, A. M. &amp; Farias-Singer, R. &amp; Ramos, R. A. &amp; Nilson, A. D." box="[886,1117,1490,1517]" pageId="8" pageNumber="161" refId="ref8113" refString="Carneiro, A. M., Farias-Singer, R., Ramos, R. A. &amp; Nilson, A. D. (2016) Cactos do Rio Grande do Sul. Fundacao Zoobotanica do Rio Grande do Sul, Porto Alegre, 224 pp." type="book" year="2016">
Carneiro 
<emphasis box="[993,1049,1490,1516]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="161">et al.</emphasis>
2016
</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="8.[136,1452,1454,1768]" pageId="8" pageNumber="161">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[189,472,1526,1552]" pageId="8" pageNumber="161">General distribution:—</emphasis>
The genus occurs from southern 
<collectingCountry box="[839,923,1526,1552]" name="Canada" pageId="8" pageNumber="161">Canada</collectingCountry>
to 
<collectingCountry box="[959,1058,1527,1553]" name="Uruguay" pageId="8" pageNumber="161">Uruguay</collectingCountry>
, with the largest number of species in 
<collectingCountry box="[165,251,1562,1588]" name="Mexico" pageId="8" pageNumber="161">Mexico</collectingCountry>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Kiesling, R." box="[265,430,1562,1589]" pageId="8" pageNumber="161" pagination="441 - 444" refId="ref8728" refString="Kiesling, R. (2005) Cactaceae. In: Burkart, A. &amp; Bacigalupo, N. (Eds.) Flora ilustrada de Entre Rios - Argentina, Tomo IV, Parte IV. Coleccion Cientifica del I. N. T. A, Buenos Aires, pp. 441 - 444." type="book chapter" year="2005">Kiesling 2005</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="8" pageNumber="161" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="8.[136,1452,1454,1768]" pageId="8" pageNumber="161">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[189,708,1598,1624]" pageId="8" pageNumber="161">Distribution in Santa Maria river basin:—</emphasis>
In SMRB only 
<taxonomicName authority="Arechavaletae (1905: 42)" authorityName="Arechavaletae" authorityPageNumber="42" authorityYear="1905" box="[888,1451,1598,1625]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Cactaceae" genus="Opuntia" kingdom="Plantae" order="Caryophyllales" pageId="8" pageNumber="161" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="megapotamica">
<emphasis box="[888,1154,1599,1625]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="161">Opuntia megapotamica</emphasis>
Arechavaletae (1905: 42)
</taxonomicName>
occurs (
<figureCitation box="[224,313,1634,1660]" captionStart="FIGURE 3" captionStartId="10.[136,229,1610,1632]" captionTargetBox="[306,1282,279,1582]" captionTargetId="figure-58@10.[302,1286,275,1586]" captionTargetPageId="10" captionText="FIGURE 3. A) Opuntia megapotamica (orange flowers). B) Parodia arnostiana (yellow flowers). C) P. herteri (pink flowers). D) P. linkii (yellow flower). E) P. mammulosa (yellow flower). F) P. nothorauschii. G) P. ottonis(flores yellow flower). H) P. ritteriana(yellow flower). I) P. tenuycilindrica. J) Wigginsiasellowii (yellow flower). K) W. langsdorffii (pale-yellow flower). L) W. turbinata (yellow flower). Pictures by A. S. Oliveira." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6415615" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6415615/files/figure.png" pageId="8" pageNumber="161">Fig. 3A</figureCitation>
) and it has a wide distribution in fields, rocky outcrops and woods.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="8.[136,1452,1454,1768]" pageId="8" pageNumber="161">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[189,448,1670,1696]" pageId="8" pageNumber="161">Morphologic notes:—</emphasis>
The species is characterized by its shrub or arboreal size, with articulated branches, acicular thorns and usually diurnal orange or yellow flowers with fleshy fruits. It blooms from October to March, bearing fruit shortly after flowering.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
